  "prompt": "What should I do if I graduated from uni 11 years ago and had only found work two years after for only a few months?",
  "response": "If you've graduated from university 11 years ago but only found work for a few months two years later, and you're looking to re-enter the job market or consider new career options, here are some steps you can take:\n\n1. **Assess Your Skills and Interests**: Take some time to reflect on your skills, interests, and values. Consider what you enjoyed studying in university and explore how those subjects can translate into career options.\n\n2. **Update Your Resume**: Create or update your resume to reflect your most recent experiences, skills, and any volunteer work or freelance projects you may have done. Consider using a functional resume format to emphasize your skills over your employment history.\n\n3. **Consider Additional Education or Training**: Depending on your field of interest, you might want to take relevant courses or certifications to update your skills or pivot to a new career. Online courses can be a flexible and economical way to gain new knowledge.\n\n4. **Network**: Connect with former classmates, professors, or colleagues. Networking can reveal job opportunities and provide valuable insights. Attend industry events, webinars, or local meetups to meet new people in your desired field.\n\n5. **Volunteer or Intern**: Gaining experience through volunteer opportunities or internships can help you build your resume, refresh your skills, and make new connections in your field.\n\n6. **Consider Temporary or Part-Time Work**: If you're open to it, consider taking temporary or part-time positions to get your foot in the door. This can help you build your work history and gain recent experience, which is valuable to potential employers.\n\n7. **Prepare for Interviews**: Be ready to explain your employment gaps positively. Focus on what you learned during the time you were not working and how it has prepared you to return to the workforce.\n\n8. **Leverage Job Search Resources**: Use online job boards, career centers, or local employment agencies to find job openings. Tailor your applications to highlight your relevant skills and experiences.\n\n9. **Stay Positive and Persistent**: Job searching can take time, especially if you've been out of the workforce for a while. Stay optimistic, be patient with yourself, and keep applying and networking.\n\n10. **Consider Career Counseling**: If you're feeling lost or overwhelmed, it may be beneficial to consult with a career counselor or coach for guidance tailored to your situation.\n\nRemember that many employers appreciate diverse life experiences, so emphasize your unique perspective and skills. Good luck!",
